ies together with fine-grained ethnographic observations and urban history to examine the ways that immigration, housing, ethnic change, gentrification, race, class, and gender have affected the neighborhood over time. Providing unique access to the nuances of inner-city life, The Tenants of East Harlem shows how roots sink so quickly in a community that has always hosted the transient, how new immigrants are challenging the claims of the old, and how that cycle is threatened as never before by the specter of gentrification.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCommunity development, UrbanxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aCommunity development, UrbanzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aEthnicityxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aEthnicityzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aGentrificationxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aGentrificationzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSociology, UrbanxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSociology, UrbanzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrban anthropologyxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aUrban anthropologyzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939547423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520939547.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles